All four scenarios you described are affected by .NET 11 breaking changes. Here's what breaks and how to fix each:

---

### 1. GZipStream empty payload (Medium impact)
GZipStream now writes valid headers/footers even when no data is written. Your zero-byte check will **never trigger** in .NET 11.

**Fix:** Check the uncompressed byte count instead of output stream length:
```csharp
// Before (.NET 10): ms.Length == 0 meant "no data"
// After (.NET 11): ms.Length > 0 always (headers/footers written)
// Fix: track whether you actually wrote any data
bool wroteData = false;
using (var gz = new GZipStream(ms, CompressionMode.Compress, leaveOpen: true))
{
    if (hasData) { gz.Write(data); wroteData = true; }
}
if (!wroteData) { /* handle "no data" */ }
```

### 2. TAR header checksum validation (Medium impact)
TAR-reading APIs now **verify checksums**. Your hand-crafted/legacy TAR files with invalid checksums will **throw exceptions**.

**Fix:** Add error handling, or fix the legacy tool to produce valid checksums:
```csharp
try
{
    using var reader = new TarReader(stream);
    var entry = reader.GetNextEntry();
}
catch (InvalidDataException ex) when (ex.Message.Contains("checksum"))
{
    // Handle legacy TAR files with bad checksums
}
```

### 3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync eager loading (Low impact)
`CreateAsync` now **eagerly loads** all entries upfront instead of lazily. For your large ZIP files this means **higher peak memory usage**.

**Fix:** Monitor memory consumption. Consider streaming entry-by-entry or processing in smaller batches if memory becomes an issue.

### 4. MemoryStream maximum capacity (Medium impact)
Maximum capacity and exception behavior have changed. Code with very large allocations near the old limit may **see different exceptions or capacity limits**.

**Fix:** Review code that creates large `MemoryStream` instances or catches specific exception types related to capacity. Adjust exception handling and validate against the new limits.

---

### TFM update needed

In your `.csproj`:
```xml
<!-- Before -->
<TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>
<!-- After -->
<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>
```

Want me to look at your actual source files and apply the fixes?
